00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:25.000
 So this chapter 8 of "The Buddhist Path" is mainly going over the story of the great master Asanga,

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
 and so maybe you thought Amanda would just kind of overview this story.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
 So then after that, we will go into these main topic points of discussion in this group.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:40.780
 So this is the chapter on "The Power of Compassion", and basically the Rinpoches start out by

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:48.000
 talking about how compassion is the most powerful tool for overcoming our karmic obscurations,

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.000
 and also for overcoming obstacles to enlightenment, so compassion being so important.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:00.970
 And then they go into this story about Asanga, who is a famous Indian scholar, about 500 years

00:03:00.970 --> 00:03:03.000
 after the Buddha's time.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:08.650
 And he was really very learned, and he still had many questions and sort of doubts that he wasn't

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:10.000
 getting resolved,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:16.000
 so he decided to go on a retreat, do practice on Maitreya, Buddha Maitreya, future Buddha.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:23.490
 So he went into retreat, and he was there for about 3 years, doing a lot of retreat on Buddha Mait

00:03:23.490 --> 00:03:24.000
reya,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
 and then after those 3 years he didn't have any signs really of having gotten to meet Maitreya,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.000
 which he really wanted, so then he decided to leave retreat.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.990
 So he was leaving retreat, and the first thing he encountered was an old man, and this man was

00:03:40.990 --> 00:03:44.000
 rubbing an iron rod with silk, a piece of silk,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
 and he was trying to make a needle out of this iron rod.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.180
 And so Asanga saw this and really just realized, wow, what patience, this is extraordinary, the

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:56.000
 patience this man has to do this.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
 I can continue my retreat, so then he decided to go back into retreat.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:06.180
 He went into retreat for 3 more years, and again he had some dreams of Maitreya, but he was really

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:09.000
 longing to meet Maitreya, and he didn't.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:16.000
 And so he left again after, so now that's 6 years, and he was leaving, and this time he was looking

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
 and he saw a pool of water and rocks,

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
 and he saw like where this one drops of water were falling on a rock and created a hole.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.420
 Just slowly, a drop by drop, this hole had been created in a rock, and he realized, oh wow, so much

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:32.000
 time, you know,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:38.110
 but look what can be done after with just diligence, and he says, okay, I'm going to go back into

00:04:38.110 --> 00:04:39.000
 retreat.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:42.000
 So he went back into retreat again for 3 more years.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.000
 Still during this time he continued to have more dreams and positive signs of Maitreya,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.460
 but then still Maitreya didn't appear to him, or at least he didn't get to ask the questions that

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:53.000
 he wanted to ask Maitreya.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:59.440
 So he left again, and this time he saw something else, he saw this rock that had become shiny from

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:00.000
 a bird,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.330
 I guess like rubbing its wings up against this rock, and again like thinking how much time that

00:05:05.330 --> 00:05:08.000
 must take for a bird's wings to create a shiny rock.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.650
 He thought, wow, you know, I could take some more time and keep trying, so he went back in again

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:15.000
 for 3 more years,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:20.000
 and still he didn't have, he didn't meet Maitreya. So this is 12 years of retreat.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:27.000
 And then after that he left, and this time he was going down the mountain, and he encountered a dog

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
 that was severely injured and wounded,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.430
 and had like I think just like the bottom half of his body was kind of his skin had been eaten, and

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:38.000
 he had maggots and fleas on his skin.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:47.530
 And so Asanga saw this and felt such compassion for this dog, contemplating the Buddha and how the

00:05:47.530 --> 00:05:48.000
 compassion of the Buddha,

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:54.000
 he decided, you know, I'm going to try to act similarly and help this dog.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.430
 And so he realized he couldn't use his hands, because he'd injured the fleas or the maggots, and so

00:05:59.430 --> 00:06:01.000
 he used his tongue.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:09.000
 And he went down, you know, and started to approach the dog to lick the maggots off the dog's skin.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
 And immediately his tongue kept hitting the ground, so he wasn't actually getting the dog.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:21.000
 And when he looked up, he saw Buddha Maitreya. So, you know, illustrating that after so much time,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
 you know, he did get to see him.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:28.200
 And Maitreya said, "The only reason I've been with you all this time, and the only reason you're

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:35.000
 only seeing me now is because due to the power of your compassion for this dog."

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
 So illustrating that point of just how powerful compassion is.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.850
 And then at the very end, Rinpoche has concluded the chapter about how really essential compassion

00:06:46.850 --> 00:06:53.000
 is, that without it, our practice is rotten.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:01.160
 So the first main topic point takes place on page 41, the first paragraph, and page 43, the last

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:02.000
 paragraph.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:07.830
 It says, "Pure compassion has the power to remove all karmic obscurations and obstacles to

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:09.000
 enlightenment.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.400
 As inner wisdom is uncovered, your understanding of relative and absolute truth increases as you

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:17.000
 progress towards enlightenment."

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.600
 The Buddha said many times that compassion is the most powerful tool for removing endurance and

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:24.000
 increasing wisdom.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:30.670
 Guru Padmasambhava taught that without compassion, Dharma practice will not bear fruit, and in fact

00:07:30.670 --> 00:07:34.000
, without compassion, your practice will become rotten.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:41.000
 So my question was just, "What makes compassion so special? Why compassion?"

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
 You know, I heard a story this weekend, actually the woman was telling me this story.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:54.870
 She had lost her daughter in a car accident about 12 years ago, and right after that, she couldn't

00:07:54.870 --> 00:07:56.000
 do Christmas.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.950
 Couldn't do Christmas at all, particularly for anyone who's lost a child, holidays become a very

00:08:00.950 --> 00:08:03.000
 hard time because they have a lot of memories.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:07.000
 So she didn't bring out the tree at all, couldn't do any of the different things.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.000
 They actually just went to Virgita. It was as good as far as ways they could.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:18.130
 And over the years, she just couldn't really bring herself around to do it. It was too painful, too

00:08:18.130 --> 00:08:19.000
 many memories.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.000
 And she has two other daughters who are now in their teens, I think.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.000
 And this year, her husband had decided to get this really big Christmas tree.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.570
 I guess for him, he'd finally come around and said, "You know, it's time he got a 12-foot Christmas

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:39.000
 tree, fill the living room."

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:46.610
 And her daughters were having this wonderful time finding Christmas ornaments, putting them up on

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:47.000
 the tree,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
 dancing around the garlands, dressing up the tree.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:57.000
 And at one point, they had realized that they didn't have enough ornaments to fill up the tree.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:03.260
 And they said, "Mom, we don't have enough ornaments." She said, "Actually, we do. They're up in the

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:04.000
 attic.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:11.000
 They're the ornaments we had from when your sister was still alive. You go up and get them."

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:17.000
 And the thing that made the story so interesting was the fact that she was saying, afterwards, she

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:17.000
's like,

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:24.300
 she could not bring herself to do that on her own. She couldn't revisit that pain for her own

00:09:24.300 --> 00:09:25.000
 benefit.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:31.000
 But when she saw her daughters having such a wonderful time, that was that thing that moved her.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:37.130
 It's like, okay, it's okay to go back there. I can have patience with that. I can be there with

00:09:37.130 --> 00:09:38.000
 that pain.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
 I can go back through that for other people.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:47.080
 It reminded me a lot of the story. Actually, it was funny. I didn't even realize the 12 years part

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:48.000
 lined up, too.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:54.460
 Because it had been 12 years since she had had a Christmas. But it's that willingness to revisit

00:09:54.460 --> 00:09:55.000
 things,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:02.260
 to go through things for other people. That's what compassion can do. Really move you beyond

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:03.000
 yourself.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:08.000
 It was just a story that reminded me of this chapter.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:18.000
 It seems like compassion is, too, that aspect. Like earlier, we were talking about loving kindness.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:24.000
 And all of this is relating back to bodhicitta, of course, but the absolute bodhicitta,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:33.230
 and then our inspiration and our vision, and just how compassion is kind of based on loving

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:34.000
 kindness,

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:42.000
 but the way compassion is actually, maybe when we begin to actualize, to actually make an outward,

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.000
 we have that love, and we have not only a love, but a desire to help,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:54.000
 and a desire to comfort beings and to uplift their minds and hearts.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:01.000
 It's kind of, in a way, maybe it's related to that actualizing power, too, as far as bodhicitta.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:12.000
 And it, of course, is based on thinking of other ascent. I mean, I think that's definitely related

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:12.000
 to that, too.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
 You know, a big thing, or something that struck me very strongly,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
 that I've heard from His Holiness Dala Lama before,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:27.490
 is he said, if we really take, or he was saying, genuine compassion is when not only we have a

00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:29.000
 natural sympathy

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:36.000
 for other beings' suffering, but we actually take responsibility to help end that suffering,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:43.050
 to do what we really can that's available to us, to take responsibility to actually remove that

00:11:43.050 --> 00:11:44.000
 suffering.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:51.000
 And it's really, the emphasis point that struck me was it really strongly, it's not just a wish,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:58.000
 there is this aspiring bodhicitta, for sure, but then it really, we have to actually engage it,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.000
 we have to, in a sense, make ourselves vulnerable, and to go into an unfamiliar thing,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
 and to really put ourselves at risk, in a way, just like in this story with the dog,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:15.000
 and just this overwhelming concern for this dog, and like, a song is probably going to get sick,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:22.000
 and he's going to get mauled by this dog, you know, when he goes down to try to save the maggots.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:29.820
 But it's the responsibility, it's not just a feel good, I'm with you, but I'm not really going to

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:30.000
 do much

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
 to actually help you, kind of a sympathy.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:41.000
 You can see there, too, like the way that relates back to the six-fire mitas,

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:49.000
 which are now part of the concepts and things, but the way the six-fire mitas are like that,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:56.000
 as far as actualizing that intention and thinking of others, you know, in a way, if you think,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
 you know, also a song that was also, he wasn't just thinking about the dog,

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:06.000
 he was thinking about like the maggots that were in the dog, and I mean, of course,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:11.000
 but just so there's like all of that generosity, there's that mindfulness,

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:16.000
 and trying out what's the most appropriate way to fix this situation, you know,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:21.000
 like really keeping like a wider vision of everything involved in it.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:27.000
 I mean, and again, I mean, obviously, he had all the patience to just get him to that point,

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.000
 but then also even with that, even being willing to deal with, you know,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:36.000
 cutting his flesh and taking the maggots out with his tongue, and all these things,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.000
 and they're just ways to relate him back, but just the way the six-fire mitas really,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:51.000
 are that part of the way of engaging and really developing our footage into, you know.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:57.000
 I mean, like I was, like about, along the same lines of everything that people have said,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
 like, why is compassion important?

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
 Like, well, if we look at the form of measurables,

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.000
 you know, beings have happiness and a cause of happiness, that's the love component.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:13.000
 May they be free from suffering and the causes of suffering.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:18.000
 So I think one of the essential points here is, everyone is kind of suffering,

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:22.000
 you know, like we're in the difficult circumstances, like,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:28.000
 and from the practical perspective, if everyone has been our mothers or our fathers

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
 or our dear friend and benefited us countless times forever, you know,

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.000
 I mean, that's what the teachings say.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:42.000
 And the only thing they want is happiness and to not have suffering,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.000
 but yet they continuously, I mean, by then, we, you know,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:51.000
 continuously engage in all these activities that are actually the causes of suffering.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:56.000
 So it's like, everyone keeps doing things that just brings more suffering,

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
 but yet everyone wants to be happy, and it's just such a, it's like, in a certain sense,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
 it's just such a poignant circumstance to see that, like,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
 and that's, again, I keep quoting this, the words of my perfect teacher Kimpo Nachum,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:14.000
 he wrote a commentary on it, and he said, what is the cause of happiness?

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:20.000
 It's the belief that in karma, so, you know, that's the vehicle of gods and humans,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
 which means you do virtuous things and therefore you obtain higher rebirths.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:29.000
 That's the, that's the, basically the Pratimonta, I mean, that's the gods and humans.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
 The second one is the wish to, the determination to attain liberation.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
 That's more like the Pratimonta, the Shravatayana, where you're like,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
 I really want to be free from samsara for myself.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
 And then the final one is, it's bodhicitta.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
 It's like, may everyone have this, may everyone, you know, enjoy the,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
 be free from the causes of suffering.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
 But, I don't know, it just seems like, along these lines,

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
 where the cult of any requirement does and everything,

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:00.000
 if your dearest mother and your kindest friend is just like,

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:05.000
 once you see clearly the situation of like, how everyone wants to be happy,

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.000
 but yet how everyone is just constantly doing things that like,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
 is the cause of unhappiness.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
 And just, not just now, but like, long into the future.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
 Then, I mean, compassion is like, that's not just a negative aspect.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
 I'm like, you could emphasize it and it could be really, you know, upsetting,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
 but in a certain sense, it is upsetting when you realize it.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
 It's just like, you know, well, everyone wants to be free from suffering,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
 but it's never going to happen.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:34.000
 And like Japa said, like, those four things, like,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
 would you take it upon yourself, you know, like,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
 wouldn't it be great if they were free from suffering, you know?

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.000
 Like, may they be free from suffering, that's the second aspiration.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
 I will be the one to do that.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
 I will be the one to leave them, that's the third aspiration.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
 And the fourth one is, praying to the three jewels and saying,

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:54.000
 please, you know, like, help me, help all these beings,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
 like, be free from suffering.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:03.000
 Anyway, I know it's a little long-winded, but it's kind of a little overview.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:07.000
 And like Maitreya, I mean, at this one last point is like,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.000
 how good of a motivation is that?

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
 That's the best motivation you could possibly have,

